When my son Noah was 3 months old, I sat next to the bed where he lay sleeping, lit some incense and I settled in for my first meditation since his birth.

I had my journal next to me and very quickly felt an urge to start writing.

“An olive branch.” I scribbled.

What came next was the most beautiful tale about a dove, who’s generosity brings regeneration to her land and community. It came out in a free flowing, pen to paper.

The Peace Dove is a heart-warming tale of giving, hope for the future and the healing that comes when we share the abundance all around us.

I truly believe that our purpose is to share our gifts with one another. 

After a year of not having this project move forward, I knew I needed not only help and expertise- but someone magically talented who connected deeply with this special story. Working with @lanabelton as my chosen illustrator has been nothing short of a gift.

This beautiful book will be available for pre-order in May 2023. If you’d like to sign up to receive email updates, I would be so grateful. All of the information is in my bio 🕊️ 

The last 2 photos are the ocean front casita where @luiskmbu28 and I lived the first 7 months 2020 and where Noah grew in my belly 🤍

The last photo is from a journal entry, 12 years ago, at a very difficult time in my life. I’m including it because, to me, it shows the wisdom we have when we listen to our intuition and honor those messages 🕊️

#ThePeaceDove #Illustrator #ChildrensBook #SelfPublishing #LandRegeneration #generosity #Kindness #Writer #Gouache #Artist #Creativity #WomenWhoRunWithTheWolves

Sounds simple but the two principles I share when I mentor photographers are 1) Boundaries and 2) Check your ENERGY and bring the BEST version of yourself to every session. 

I encourage photographers to say positive mantras before their sessions (I do 🥳🙏)!

Some questions you can ask yourself before stepping into someone’s love bubble and photographing them:

🧐 How do I feel right now?
🦋 What can I do even better than my last session?
🌙 Mantra: This session is going to be so magical and beautiful, the couple will be so in love and we will have the BEST time together ☁️

Might sound cheesy, but positive affirmations, preparation and having a growth mindset really do make a massive difference in the quality of your work, your client’s experience and your overall career as a photographer ☁️

I have a photography mentorship starting in March, jumó in my DMs if you’re ready to take that camera, kickoff your shoes (we love working bare foot 😉) and run around in the sunset 🌅 capturing love. It’s the best ✨

it doesn't interest me what you do for a living. I want to know what you ache for and if you dare to dream of meeting your heart's longing.

It doesn't interest me how old you are. I want to know if you will risk looking like a fool for love for your dream for the adventure of being alive.

it doesn't interest me what planets are squaring your moon... I want to know if you have touched the centre of your own sorrow if you have been opened by life's betrayals or have become shrivelled and closed from fear of further pain.

I want to know if you can sit with pain mine or your own without moving to hide it or fade it or fix it. I want to know if you can be with joy mine or your own if you can dance with wildness and let the ecstasy fill you to the tips of your fingers and toes without cautioning us to be careful to be realistic to remember the limitations of being human.

It doesn't interest me if the story you are telling me is true. I want to know if you can disappoint another to be true to yourself. If you can bear the accusation of betrayal and not betray your own soul. If you can be faithless and therefore trustworthy.

I want to know if you can see Beauty even when it is not pretty every day. And if you can source your own life from its presence. I want to know if you can live with failure yours and mine and still stand at the edge of the lake and shout to the silver of the full moon, "Yes."

It doesn't interest me to know where you live or how much money you have. I want to know if you can get up after the night of grief and despair weary and bruised to the bone and do what needs to be done to feed the children.

it doesn't interest me who you know or how you came to be here. I want to know if you will stand in the centre of the fire with me and not shrink back.

It doesn't interest me where or what or with whom you have studied. I want to know what sustains you from the inside when all else falls away.

I want to know if you can be alone with yourself and if you truly like the company you keep in the empty moments.

- @Oriah Mountain Dreamer 
@the_wildhive

Take pictures of your life now.
Don’t wait for an ideal circumstance, a better outfit, a cleaner house, a different body or some other thing that isn’t available in this very moment.

I’ve been busy shooting other families, other people. I can’t remember the last time I brought my camera out to photograph my own little family. Growing, playing, being.

If you take anything away from this reel, go out and grab your camera and take pictures of your life now 📸✨ Hand your camera over to your family members and friends, BE in the photos. Capture your loves and life 🤍✨

If you’re interested in learning how to use your camera and how to shoot on manual, I teach photography and have a few incredible courses (Photo 101 & Editing 101 - oh and a photography mentorship that is next level 🦋).
If you have questions or are interested, please shoot me a DM, I’d love to help you become a better photographer 🧚‍♀️

We didn’t know we were going to buy this land. I really thought it was out of reach.

But since landing in this tiny town 3.5 years ago, I couldn’t stop pondering this idea of a Women’s Artist Residency.

This week we are putting the roof on what will be an art gallery and residency (and our home - and a pizzeria).

Your vision and goals have the power to shape your reality. They give you direction, purpose, and the motivation to keep pushing forward. When you set your sights on something, the universe conspires to help you make it happen. 

I started sharing my gift and love for photography with women. If you’ve ever hired me, signed up for Photo 101 or been a part of my transformational mentorship’s- know that you have helped make this all happen and my gratitude is so deep. We’ve sunk every single penny into this dream and it’s happening. I can’t wait to welcome artists from all over the world. I can’t wait to see the way this work uplifts our local community of women. My soul is on fire 🥹🕊️

So, I guess I’m saying: dream big, set your goals high, and watch as your vision becomes a reality.

I am co-hosting a vision and goals workshop for women signed up for Together (see highlights) this upcoming Tuesday.

Mini Session Moments 🥹✨ 🤓 

I often talk about legacy and what that means in relation to the work that I do. It’s a theme and value I like to encourage and instill in my photography students because when you capture a portrait, a moment shared, a friendship, a love- you capture it forever for someone. 

Photographers are hired for mostly happy moments but we also get called to celebrate and capture difficult moments, moments of grief. We get called when someone passes on with “can you find this picture” or “that moment”. Photos are used to celebrate and remember and that is powerful legacy.

This little moment, shared between father and son was so light-hearted and sweet. And that is the legacy they can remember from these toddler years: silly, playful, funny.

Grateful to teach photography, guide others on this beautiful path and to be an ambassador for great photographer gallery platform for @pictime_us (if you’re a photographer and not using Pic-Time, use my code PANTELPHOTO to get an extra free month, it’ll level your business UP📸✨)

Hello from the edge of the Pacific, where the jungle kisses the sea.

The mid-morning rain pushes a cool breeze onto our broken, terracotta balcony where I sit. The horizon line is soft and creamy. A melting of sorts between sea and sky.

It’s humpback season, where beyond the first reef and before the second they’ll make their great migration from the Antarctic and Chile to Peru, Ecuador, Colombia, Costa Rica and here, in Panamá.

It’s the only migration that involves crossing the Equator and it’s here, I read, in these warm waters, that they feel safe to birth their calves.

A refuge to raise their young.

I look over to my son, babbling in part Spanish, part English, part toddler, going on about what the Polar Bear, Polar Bear, hears and in the very next breath singing his own rendition of Slippery Fish.

Like the whales, I feel too that this place is a refuge to raise my son.

Many of you have been following my journey, from Canada to Panama. In the midst of the pandemic, falling in love, making and birthing our beautiful son in a tiny thatched roof casita nestled on the edge of the ocean in a foreign country.

Following my discovery of an entirely new culture and a deeper sense of self through motherhood and the great seasons of life.

Watching me connect with the most gorgeous community of women in ceremonies of cacao by the fire and next to the roaring sea.

It’s here, I’ll be sharing a deeper, more intimate look into the stories that have shaped me over the past 4 years. Many of which I’ve guarded with my life. But as time does its thing, I feel more peace and healing than I could have ever imagined.

And now, I acknowledge a truth that has become rather impossible to ignore.

I am a writer, but I do not write.

Stories can liberate us and they can break us. The magic happens, I believe, when the latter comes first.

It is story that brings us together and reminds us of our connection. 

Of our humanity.

And so, I write.

Thank you for being here as I share my Conversations with the Moon & Other Tales from the Jungle.

Monique

“Perhaps (surely) inviting the unavoidable wholeheartedly will lull the waves, bringing calmer waters. Perhaps (surely) on the other side of the cocoon lies a metamorphosis you couldn’t begin to fathom: the caterpillar who once crawled becomes the butterfly, who now flies.” 🦋

In my latest #substack, I’ve written a short piece for women in your life who’ve found themselves in a self-inflicted purgatory - or a season of change. Please share with them 🦋 

Finding time and space for creative writing, nature and life’s gifts lately.

Really enjoying the @substackinc platform 📓✏️

We watched it happen this morning over breakfast, our eyes scanning the sea for the mother and calf humpback that have been calling our beach break home for the past several days. I suppose it’s more their beach break than ours, but it’s where our community gathers and we’re all so thrilled they're here. Grey skies let down the rain and within moments, the waves had become flat, water calmed. The whales were even more visible now.

Did you know that waves lull when it rains? I didn't.

We stood barefoot on the black sandy shores communally hushed and giddy over the sight of mama humpback and baby humpback breaching, waving, spouting, and spraying. There’s such a quiet, shared delight in watching whales.

They’re seasonal here, but the butterflies you’ll find year-round. Speckled orange and black monarchs, blue morphos - which are actually moths - and plenty of little yellow ones that tend to flutter around in pairs. Those ones are my favorite.

I began writing this for myself, about myself, but I’ve realized I’ve got a handful of dear friends who are on the precipice of their own emergence.

The miraculous moment a butterfly breaks from its cocoon is: emergence. 

Before this can happen, she must garner enough strength to break the cocoon open, so she can begin to fly.

Emergence. To arise, to rise up, to come up or to come forth.

The months pass, and I continue to watch my dear friends, entirely exhausted from trying to avoid the storm and drowning in their own personal, capsizing waves: affairs, death, illness, divorce, career pivots. 

Avoid the rain, endure the waves. 

Purgatory can be self-inflicted, too.

Ask me about photography and I will tell you about legacy. Happiness and heartbreak are etched into our skin over time, like water wears into stone, marks that whisper rememberings of who we’ve loved, ways we have lost and the privilege - and hopefully joy - to live another day. 

Debbie, in the middle, brought her daughter and granddaughter on a yoga retreat. My heart skipped- a generational portrait… yessss!

I got to chat briefly with her about life and I started talking about motherhood and the inevitable seasons of change. 

“It’s how you walk through them.” she responded.

I don’t think I’ll ever forget that simple piece of wisdom, that although life has inevitable seasons of change, that it really matters most the way we walk through them.
My whole heart 🤍

The best camera is…👇🏼📸

The one that’s sitting in your closet or the one you can borrow from your uncle Bill. Once you shift your camera setting to manual- it’s (almost) all the same.

I get this question every day and- I promise you - it’s not about the newest, shiniest, most expensive camera. 

It’s about empowering yourself to LEARN how to use a camera on manual, to LEARN about equipment, lenses, composition and all the things that contribute to making a beautiful photo.

Save yourself thousands of dollars and just take a simple photography course (like Photo 101, with me 👋🏼) where I break down everything you need to get started FAST in taking beautiful photos.

Once you have a solid understanding of camera mechanics, I even have suggestions for a variety of equipment and lenses within my courses ☺️📸 

You’re going to feel so confident walking into the camera store knowing exactly what you want, why you want it and how much you’re going to invest in your new equipment 🦋 It’s the best feeling!

Do you want to improve your photography and ACTUALLY learn how to use your camera?…

We have been wading in a season of transition. I stopped nursing Noah recently on account of he was probably ready, and that I had to travel and really didn’t want to deal with a mastitis blow up whilst away for work. We’ve all been sleeping better since we ended that journey.

Arizona was wonderful. I got to spend time with my precious teen angels that are growing into beautiful young women. My heart soars. I got to photograph a gorgeous wedding in the shadows of Camelback mountain and visited with old friends. I watched the Bourdain doc on the plane on the way home and my heart broke for how sad, alone and betrayed he felt at the end of his life. I love any art that makes me feel more human. 

I can feel we are almost on the other side of this particular transition. We bought patio furniture, our home is slowly being landscaped. We still don’t have a couch but I ordered a Christmas tree that arrived yesterday, though I’m still unsure if my parents will travel here, we may come to Canada or it’s possible we wait until spring. 

I’m into week 2 of leading my photography mentorship, which never fails to make me cry because watching women step into themselves and find a new layer of confidence and creativity never fails to move me. I always say, I’m just a mirror, showing you how great you actually are, that you have gifts to share, you just need to see it and believe it for yourself. We’re flowing and still have 4 weeks to go 🕊

Next week I will be in San Fransisco shooting an amazing summit. I’ve met some incredible people and just can’t wait to be around that energy again.

My retreat in Panama Feb 4-10 has a few spots left and if you’ve been considering joining, we’d love to have you. Art, nature, adventure and creativity every day. Ocean front rooms. A new moon cacao ceremony on the Friday. If you need more info it’s in my bio or you can just DM me, I’m here 🥹🦋

I hope to find time to write more, but I am a bit backlogged with some editing and commitments. Life flows and I’m leaning into Annie’s mac and cheese saving the day more often than I’d like to admit. 

I could ramble on but i just want to say I love you and thanks for being here 🕊

Tomorrow marks four years since I took a last minute flight to Panama, which shifted my entire life trajectory. Or, in a truer sense, and in hindsight, brought me back on the path I feel I was always meant for. I could say a lot more, mostly about following your heart and that you are deserving of the most love, but for now, I’m about to hop on a motorcycle with my hot baby daddy and our toddler and go play in a waterfall 🥳🍄🌈🦋🌊🕊🤍💫 @luiskmbu28

You built a life under ten moons 🌙
you were a house of water
you held a second heart in the 
arms of your rib cage
dreamed two sets of dreams
merged the rivers of your 
bloodlines under your skin
and then, in the early hours of a spring morning
i watched a piece of you leave
swallowed in the pain of your shattering
you broke, and the rains of new life 
poured out of you

you are now the mother of that dawning ground
the guardian of its soil
the mender of its aching
the gardener of its joy
this is your work now

you were born in your dying
you were delivered to a new life as you birthed 
one into existence

you are utter magic
building that mountain

HERE’S HOW 👇🏼 

First, make sure to save this post so you can come back to it.

Carve out 10 minutes and take the time to take photos. Don’t overcomplicated it.

Use these tips to create beautiful holiday photos that tell a story and capture memories.

🎁 Use window light and daylight. Don’t forget to turn off lamps and pot lights lights. Keep the tree lights on!

🎁 Give Portrait mode a try on your phone (click f and adjust to 2.0). Focus on different  things: tiny hands holding ornaments, lights, expressions.

🎁 Make it fun! Give your family prompts to do something- touch that ornament, hold this light, shake this present and guess what’s inside!

1️⃣ Use a self timer app to get the whole group in the shot - I love “Lens Buddy”

2️⃣ Get your partner or friend to take photos of YOU WITH your littles. 

3️⃣ Spray and pray: Take more photos than you actually need. You can delete later.

4️⃣ Edit with a holiday preset to make your photos shine!!! 💫
